1
00:00:33,657 --> 00:00:34,924
I hate to tell you this,

2
00:00:34,992 --> 00:00:36,659
but he does not want to be a doctor when he grows up.

3
00:00:36,727 --> 00:00:39,295
He let me know this morning he would like to be a mail carrier.

4
00:00:39,806 --> 00:00:41,030
From a doctor to a mail carrier.

5
00:00:41,098 --> 00:00:43,032
Who works for the Pony Express.

6
00:00:44,268 --> 00:00:45,368
Wait a minute.

7
00:00:45,436 --> 00:00:46,803
Were there any ghosts involved in this last night?

8
00:00:46,870 --> 00:00:48,604
No, we were just watching an old western on tv.

9
00:00:48,672 --> 00:00:50,273
You know what, not everything is paranormal.

10
00:00:50,340 --> 00:00:51,808
Some things are just normal.

11
00:00:51,875 --> 00:00:53,643
Not usually between the two of us.

12
00:00:53,711 --> 00:00:58,114
Come on, it's heartburn from that damn keen-wa stir-fry.

13
00:00:58,182 --> 00:01:00,550
Your little health nut friend better start working on his English.

14
00:01:00,617 --> 00:01:02,919
I told him "no peppers," not "mo' peppers."

15
00:01:02,986 --> 00:01:05,621
Ray, I know you scarfed a foot-long from the street cart.

16
00:01:05,689 --> 00:01:07,156
There's mustard on your tie.

17
00:01:07,224 --> 00:01:08,891
What is Eli's dad doing here?

18
00:01:08,959 --> 00:01:09,892
Mr. James?

19
00:01:09,960 --> 00:01:11,227
What? Melanie?

20
00:01:11,295 --> 00:01:12,562
What the hell are you doing here?

21
00:01:12,629 --> 00:01:14,731
Melinda. This is my husband. He's a doctor here.

22
00:01:14,798 --> 00:01:16,632
- Are you ok?  - I'm fine.

23
00:01:16,700 --> 00:01:19,235
I mean Case here's worked up over a bout of indigestion.

24
00:01:19,303 --> 00:01:21,237
- It's nothing.  - He's having trouble breathing,

25
00:01:21,305 --> 00:01:22,405
Chest pains.

26
00:01:22,473 --> 00:01:24,040
Feeling any numbness in your left arm

27
00:01:24,108 --> 00:01:25,174
or any pain in your jaw?

28
00:01:25,242 --> 00:01:27,176
Of course I'm numb and in pain. I'm old.

29
00:01:27,244 --> 00:01:29,946
But I'm leaving here before you charge me for talking to you.

30
00:01:30,013 --> 00:01:31,748
Mr. James, you could be having a heart attack, ok?

31
00:01:31,815 --> 00:01:33,649
An actual coronary. I need a wheelchair.

32
00:01:33,717 --> 00:01:35,251
Look, my coronary is fine.

33
00:01:35,319 --> 00:01:38,588
I just need to get back on the "shut up, Casey" diet.

34
00:01:38,655 --> 00:01:40,690
The only reason I do it is so she'll stop nagging me.

35
00:01:40,758 --> 00:01:42,258
I pay her to keep the books,

36
00:01:42,326 --> 00:01:45,928
Not harass me every time I look longingly at...

37
00:01:45,996 --> 00:01:47,096
A damn French...

38
00:01:47,164 --> 00:01:48,464
Mr. James?

39
00:01:48,532 --> 00:01:49,832
It's gas.

40
00:01:49,900 --> 00:01:50,933
Everybody, stand back.

41
00:01:53,470 --> 00:01:55,404
Wait a minute. We need a cardio work-up now.

42
00:01:55,472 --> 00:01:57,907
Mr. James, you're gonna be all right.

43
00:01:57,975 --> 00:01:59,542
- Go, go. Take her.  - Casey!

44
00:01:59,610 --> 00:02:00,743
We'll look after him.

45
00:02:00,811 --> 00:02:02,173
I got your message. What's going on?

46
00:02:02,173 --> 00:02:03,746
Your dad might be having a heart attack.

47
00:02:03,814 --> 00:02:05,581
- Dad!  - Don't "dad" me.

48
00:02:05,649 --> 00:02:07,283
It's not a heart attack. I just need a bromo.

49
00:02:07,351 --> 00:02:10,419
He came into the shop after lunch complaining of chest pains.

50
00:02:10,487 --> 00:02:12,522
He should have retired years ago.

51
00:02:12,589 --> 00:02:13,473
Are you kidding me?

52
00:02:13,473 --> 00:02:16,651
The screen door king's not abdicating anytime soon.

53
00:02:16,651 --> 00:02:17,960
Hi. Um, I'm Casey.

54
00:02:18,028 --> 00:02:19,962
My mom and Eli's dad are business partners.

55
00:02:20,030 --> 00:02:21,697
Right. We met at the grand reopening.

56
00:02:21,765 --> 00:02:23,099
God, I sure hope he's ok.

57
00:02:23,167 --> 00:02:24,667
He's fine. Excuse me.

58
00:02:24,735 --> 00:02:26,903
Now, come on, take your mind off it.

59
00:02:35,612 --> 00:02:36,946
You're Eli's mom.

60
00:02:37,014 --> 00:02:38,281
Evelyn.

61
00:02:38,348 --> 00:02:41,083
I'm sorry. I've never been very good at charades.

62
00:02:41,151 --> 00:02:42,418
I don't understand.

63
00:02:42,486 --> 00:02:44,844
Eli told me that you died 7 years ago.

64
00:02:44,844 --> 00:02:46,255
We both thought you went into the light.

65
00:02:46,323 --> 00:02:48,491
Nope, not me. Not yet.

66
00:02:48,559 --> 00:02:50,278
Well, if there's something keeping you here,

67
00:02:50,278 --> 00:02:51,190
you know that Eli can help.

68
00:02:51,190 --> 00:02:52,929
I mean, did you know that he can hear you?

69
00:02:52,996 --> 00:02:55,097
Oh, yes. People gossip on this side,

70
00:02:55,165 --> 00:02:57,400
And I check in on him from time to time,

71
00:02:57,467 --> 00:03:00,870
But you never know what you might pop in on, so.

72
00:03:00,938 --> 00:03:02,972
Well, haven't you ever wanted to talk to him?

73
00:03:03,040 --> 00:03:04,740
Of course I have.

74
00:03:04,808 --> 00:03:07,643
But what man wants to be haunted by his mother?

75
00:03:07,711 --> 00:03:09,445
Besides, I need your help.

76
00:03:09,513 --> 00:03:11,714
Ok, but Eli's your son.

77
00:03:11,782 --> 00:03:12,934
I mean, it might be good for both of you...

78
00:03:12,934 --> 00:03:15,144
It's not for me. It's for Ray.

79
00:03:15,144 --> 00:03:16,519
He's not well, you know.

80
00:03:16,587 --> 00:03:18,921
He's going to be on this side soon.

81
00:03:18,989 --> 00:03:21,636
Very soon.

82
00:03:22,226 --> 00:03:23,226
I should call my mom.

83
00:03:23,293 --> 00:03:25,094
That's gonna be really hard for Eli.

84
00:03:25,162 --> 00:03:26,596
Exactly.

85
00:03:28,064 --> 00:03:30,266
And he'll want to help his father.

86
00:03:30,334 --> 00:03:32,168
That's the kind of man he is.

87
00:03:32,236 --> 00:03:34,737
But that wouldn't be the brightest idea.

88
00:03:34,805 --> 00:03:36,172
The two of them have never real...

89
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:37,773
Oh, no.

90
00:03:39,369 --> 00:03:40,443
Cut the chit-chat.

91
00:03:40,510 --> 00:03:42,111
Let's get the hell out of here, huh.

92
00:03:42,179 --> 00:03:43,779
Come on, I'm as fit as a fiddle now.

93
00:03:43,847 --> 00:03:45,748
Let's go. Chop-chop.

94
00:03:45,816 --> 00:03:46,949
What's wrong?

95
00:03:47,017 --> 00:03:49,685
I think my dad's...dead.

96
00:03:49,753 --> 00:03:51,153
You don't know that.

97
00:03:51,221 --> 00:03:53,289
What the hell?

98
00:03:56,493 --> 00:03:57,860
Eli,

99
00:03:57,928 --> 00:04:00,798
Your dad went into full arrest while he was being evaluated.

100
00:04:00,798 --> 00:04:03,165
We did everything we could.

101
00:04:03,233 --> 00:04:04,867
I'm so sorry, Eli.

102
00:04:04,935 --> 00:04:07,036
Oh, my god.

103
00:04:07,104 --> 00:04:09,338
Oh, Eli.

104
00:04:09,406 --> 00:04:11,007
Wait.

105
00:04:11,074 --> 00:04:13,935
I'm...I'm dead?

106
00:04:13,935 --> 00:04:16,212
But I'm still here?

107
00:04:16,280 --> 00:04:18,770
That's usually how it works.

108
00:04:18,949 --> 00:04:20,182
What?

109
00:04:20,250 --> 00:04:21,417
Eli.

110
00:04:21,485 --> 00:04:23,052
Ok, smart guy.

111
00:04:23,120 --> 00:04:24,887
If you know so much about death,

112
00:04:24,955 --> 00:04:27,022
Where the hell is your mother?

113
00:04:27,328 --> 00:04:31,027
Get him into the light. Fast. Soon. Now.

114
00:04:31,094 --> 00:04:32,361
Well, can't you help me?

115
00:04:32,429 --> 00:04:33,529
I mean, Eli's your son.

116
00:04:33,597 --> 00:04:34,597
He just lost his father.

117
00:04:34,665 --> 00:04:36,832
Oh, no. Just please, handle it.

118
00:04:36,900 --> 00:04:39,101
And as far as our little chat,

119
00:04:39,169 --> 00:04:41,086
I was never here.

120
00:05:26,692 --> 00:05:27,894
You want some more wine?

121
00:05:27,961 --> 00:05:30,029
No, thanks.

122
00:05:30,097 --> 00:05:31,531
I have to go home tonight,

123
00:05:32,227 --> 00:05:33,833
Start reading dad's will,

124
00:05:33,901 --> 00:05:35,234
planning his funeral.

125
00:05:35,302 --> 00:05:37,782
I'm still shocked he trusted me to be the executor.

126
00:05:37,904 --> 00:05:39,872
I take it you two didn't get along?

127
00:05:39,940 --> 00:05:41,374
Not exactly.

128
00:05:41,442 --> 00:05:44,410
Dad wanted me to be the next Screen Door King,

129
00:05:44,478 --> 00:05:46,479
Not some touchy-feely shrink.

130
00:05:46,547 --> 00:05:48,181
He thought I was a flake.

131
00:05:48,181 --> 00:05:50,983
The last couple of years we barely spoke since I told him about the ghosts.

132
00:05:51,051 --> 00:05:52,318
He didn't believe you?

133
00:05:52,386 --> 00:05:54,120
He wanted me to prove it by talking to my mom,

134
00:05:54,188 --> 00:05:55,254
But she's gone.

135
00:05:55,322 --> 00:05:56,823
And now he's off looking for her.

136
00:05:56,890 --> 00:05:58,658
What did he say right before he disappeared?

137
00:05:58,725 --> 00:06:00,626
Just that he wanted to see my mom.

138
00:06:00,694 --> 00:06:03,396
I tried to tell him that she's already waiting for him in the light.

139
00:06:03,464 --> 00:06:04,831
He never listens to me.

140
00:06:04,898 --> 00:06:06,899
Anyway, I guess I should call Case.

141
00:06:06,967 --> 00:06:08,501
She said she'd help with everything.

142
00:06:08,569 --> 00:06:09,502
Hey, what's the story with that?

143
00:06:09,570 --> 00:06:10,762
You guys had a major vibe going on.

144
00:06:10,762 --> 00:06:11,897
Yeah, but what's the point?

145
00:06:11,897 --> 00:06:14,044
Every woman I've dated the past 6 years bolts

146
00:06:14,044 --> 00:06:15,975
as soon as I bring up the ghosts.

147
00:06:16,043 --> 00:06:18,678
Hey, there might be one that surprises you.

148
00:06:18,745 --> 00:06:19,679
Easy for you to say.

149
00:06:19,746 --> 00:06:20,813
Baby, what are you working on?

150
00:06:20,881 --> 00:06:22,115
Aw, is that you and your daddy?

151
00:06:22,182 --> 00:06:25,184
It's Uncle Eli and his dad at a lake.

152
00:06:25,252 --> 00:06:27,120
And this is the cabin.

153
00:06:27,187 --> 00:06:29,689
We used to have a house at the lake.

154
00:06:29,756 --> 00:06:32,792
Spent every summer up there with Casey and her folks.

155
00:06:32,860 --> 00:06:33,960
What's that?

156
00:06:38,232 --> 00:06:40,233
I think it means "stop."

157
00:06:40,741 --> 00:06:45,000
Aiden, the sitter said that you started this before school.

158
00:06:45,706 --> 00:06:48,441
I thought Uncle Eli might be sad today.

159
00:06:49,062 --> 00:06:52,096
Ok. Um, why don't we finish it in the morning? Right?

160
00:06:52,096 --> 00:06:53,846
And for now, brush those teeth.

161
00:06:53,914 --> 00:06:57,425
Come on, little man. Oh. It's the time.

162
00:06:58,685 --> 00:07:00,786
Don't you find that creepy?

163
00:07:00,854 --> 00:07:02,955
How did he know I had a lake house?

164
00:07:03,023 --> 00:07:05,658
The same way that he thought you were gonna be sad,

165
00:07:05,726 --> 00:07:08,628
- He knew your dad was sick.  - Spooky.

166
00:07:11,732 --> 00:07:14,600
My mother died up there... aneurysm.

167
00:07:14,668 --> 00:07:17,203
Dad found her on the bathroom floor,

168
00:07:17,271 --> 00:07:19,205
Sold the place right after.

169
00:07:19,273 --> 00:07:21,974
Were things good between your parents when she passed?

170
00:07:22,042 --> 00:07:23,009
Who knows?

171
00:07:23,076 --> 00:07:24,582
But obviously, she was at peace,

172
00:07:24,582 --> 00:07:27,013
Or otherwise, she'd be hanging around here. Why do you ask?

173
00:07:27,080 --> 00:07:29,615
I was just wondering. What about your mom's family?

174
00:07:29,683 --> 00:07:32,218
- Any issues there?  - My mom's family?

175
00:07:32,286 --> 00:07:35,221
None that I'm aware of. Why?

176
00:07:35,289 --> 00:07:38,958
Uh, it's just, you know, covering all the bases.

177
00:07:41,094 --> 00:07:43,873
I just lost my father, sort of,

178
00:07:44,025 --> 00:07:46,646
and you're asking about my mom?

179
00:07:48,033 --> 00:07:50,002
She came to me this afternoon.

180
00:07:50,070 --> 00:07:53,005
My mother? She's still here? What did she say?

181
00:07:53,073 --> 00:07:56,107
Just that she wanted me to help your father go into the light.

182
00:07:56,108 --> 00:07:59,378
But look, she really didn't seem like she wanted to go with him. So...

183
00:07:59,446 --> 00:08:01,314
Wait, wait. What? Why not?

184
00:08:01,381 --> 00:08:04,150
I don't know. I don't know, but I'll figure it out,

185
00:08:04,218 --> 00:08:06,219
And I'll get them to cross over, ok? I promise.

186
00:08:06,286 --> 00:08:08,654
Evelyn's still here?

187
00:08:08,722 --> 00:08:11,324
Heh. I guess that's another thing you got wrong, boy, huh?

188
00:08:11,391 --> 00:08:13,603
Ok. You know what? Mr. James, really, If you could...

189
00:08:13,604 --> 00:08:17,376
Oh, no, no. I spent all day looking for a damn light. Thanks to you.

190
00:08:17,376 --> 00:08:19,665
And now I find out that she's still hanging around?

191
00:08:19,733 --> 00:08:24,604
No, I gotta find her. Evelyn? Evelyn!

192
00:08:24,671 --> 00:08:26,405
Feel free to retract your offer.

193
00:08:31,724 --> 00:08:33,579
It's almost like he's still here.

194
00:08:37,050 --> 00:08:38,818
Not at the moment.

195
00:08:38,885 --> 00:08:41,254
Look, I don't even know if I can do this.

196
00:08:41,321 --> 00:08:43,923
Ok, come on. Let's just find his suit and go. Ok?

197
00:08:43,991 --> 00:08:46,859
I'll even take it by the funeral home if you want.

198
00:08:46,927 --> 00:08:49,128
You're the best.

199
00:08:52,232 --> 00:08:55,968
The doctor told him he should stop drinking. Typical dad.

200
00:08:56,036 --> 00:08:59,238
Yeah, he still had one Manhattan a day. Said he liked the ritual.

201
00:08:59,306 --> 00:09:01,474
Well, then I say we have one in his honor.

202
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:02,942
Might make this a little bit easier.

203
00:09:03,010 --> 00:09:05,011
I like the way you think.

204
00:09:06,728 --> 00:09:10,483
So, uh, is your girlfriend coming to the funeral?

205
00:09:10,550 --> 00:09:13,252
Oh, that'll be a little bit hard since she's nonexistent

206
00:09:13,320 --> 00:09:15,321
Oh, you...you broke up?

207
00:09:16,356 --> 00:09:19,292
16 times. 16 different women.

208
00:09:19,359 --> 00:09:22,185
Really? Your dad said you were

209
00:09:22,186 --> 00:09:24,096
seeing somebody pretty seriously for the past few years.

210
00:09:24,164 --> 00:09:26,465
Well, then he's confusing me with the son he wish he had.

211
00:09:26,950 --> 00:09:31,637
Or ignoring the one that he did, mm-mmm, terminally single.

212
00:09:31,705 --> 00:09:33,172
How about you?

213
00:09:33,240 --> 00:09:36,142
Dad said you're engaged to some airline pilot?

214
00:09:36,209 --> 00:09:40,226
Chad? Uh, no.

215
00:09:40,226 --> 00:09:42,381
Turns out he had a girl in every airport.

216
00:09:42,449 --> 00:09:44,116
Plus, that was ages ago.

217
00:09:44,184 --> 00:09:46,185
I mean, I've been out a couple times since,

218
00:09:46,253 --> 00:09:49,288
But...Ray must have been confused.

219
00:09:49,356 --> 00:09:52,325
Or something. Here you go.

220
00:09:54,461 --> 00:09:57,299
To the screen door king

221
00:09:57,299 --> 00:10:00,266
and to seeing you again.

222
00:10:04,614 --> 00:10:06,558
They seem like such a happy family.

223
00:10:06,696 --> 00:10:09,799
As happy as anybody, I guess.

224
00:10:09,866 --> 00:10:12,015
And, uh, this one was taken at the lake house?

225
00:10:12,015 --> 00:10:14,837
Our two families spent a lot of time up there back then.

226
00:10:14,905 --> 00:10:17,807
And that is our Casey and Eli.

227
00:10:17,874 --> 00:10:19,475
Those two loved going up there.

228
00:10:19,543 --> 00:10:20,876
When Ray and Evelyn bought it,

229
00:10:20,944 --> 00:10:21,977
He made all the screen doors,

230
00:10:22,045 --> 00:10:24,113
And I said they were good enough to sell.

231
00:10:24,181 --> 00:10:26,916
Don's the one who suggested we start a business.

232
00:10:26,983 --> 00:10:28,050
The four of you?

233
00:10:28,118 --> 00:10:30,386
Oh, no, no, no. This was all Ray and Anne's.

234
00:10:30,454 --> 00:10:32,421
I'm retired. Public Defender.

235
00:10:32,489 --> 00:10:36,158
Don worked such long hours, and I needed something to do, so.

236
00:10:36,226 --> 00:10:38,623
- This is Eli's mom?  - Yes, Evelyn.

237
00:10:38,623 --> 00:10:40,663
She passed away before we met.

238
00:10:40,730 --> 00:10:43,532
She was a lovely person.

239
00:10:43,600 --> 00:10:45,968
So I've gathered.

240
00:10:46,036 --> 00:10:48,437
Look, this is gonna sound like a strange question,

241
00:10:48,505 --> 00:10:49,756
But was there any reason that

242
00:10:49,757 --> 00:10:52,975
she would have been angry with her husband before she died?

243
00:10:53,043 --> 00:10:54,944
That is a strange question.

244
00:10:55,011 --> 00:10:58,047
It's just that Eli's been so torn up about the whole thing.

245
00:10:58,114 --> 00:11:00,716
And last night he was... he was wondering

246
00:11:00,784 --> 00:11:02,117
If his parents are together now.

247
00:11:02,818 --> 00:11:04,220
Why wouldn't they be?

248
00:11:04,287 --> 00:11:06,956
I mean, if you believe in that sort of stuff.

249
00:11:07,023 --> 00:11:11,660
Of course. Um, sorry to have bothered you.

250
00:11:11,728 --> 00:11:13,496
And I'm sorry for your loss.

251
00:11:18,935 --> 00:11:22,938
That's the screen door that Ray made for the lake house.

252
00:11:25,345 --> 00:11:26,809
Anne, where are you?

253
00:11:26,877 --> 00:11:29,912
I'm sorry, Don. I'm stuck at the shop a few more hours.

254
00:11:30,600 --> 00:11:31,833
Ray!

255
00:11:34,652 --> 00:11:36,885
Are you ok?

256
00:11:37,892 --> 00:11:40,872
Yeah. I'm fine.

257
00:11:41,324 --> 00:11:43,893
Thank you for your time.

258
00:11:49,733 --> 00:11:51,166
What are you looking for?

259
00:11:51,234 --> 00:11:53,202
My dad's favorite cufflinks.

260
00:11:53,270 --> 00:11:55,337
The ones with the little screen doors on them.

